		<outline text="9/1/2016" created="Thu, 01 Sep 2016 14:26:32 GMT" >
			<outline text="Can't run out the clock" created="Thu, 01 Sep 2016 14:26:32 GMT" type="outline" >
				<outline text="Nate &lt;a href=&quot;http://fivethirtyeight.com/features/election-update-as-the-race-tightens-dont-assume-the-electoral-college-will-save-clinton/&quot;&gt;says&lt;/a&gt; don't count on the Electoral College saving us.&amp;nbsp;&lt;span&gt;Good point. The latest polls show the race narrowing.&lt;/span&gt;" created="Thu, 01 Sep 2016 14:26:33 GMT" />
				<outline text="And even worse, Trump now can read off a teleprompter without sacrificing quality. Which means writers can create for his medium. And worse it shows that he's been taking lessons, and as an actor he's good at performing with a teleprompter. And it's even worse -- he's got great writers, they may be fascists, but they can spin a good story, as evidenced from the crowd screams last night.&amp;nbsp;" created="Thu, 01 Sep 2016 14:26:34 GMT" />
				<outline text="&lt;span&gt;I would also assume he's also being schooled in debating. There will be a surprise when he takes the stage with Hillary in a month or so.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span&gt;Yeah he says he isn't rehearsing. That's spin. Setting expectations. Don't believe it. He's taking lessons and he's figuring it out.&lt;/span&gt;" created="Thu, 01 Sep 2016 14:26:35 GMT" />
				<outline text="We need to be smart, now. No running out the clock this year." created="Thu, 01 Sep 2016 14:26:36 GMT" />
				</outline>
			<outline text="Streaking and leaking" created="Thu, 01 Sep 2016 16:06:08 GMT" type="outline" >
				<outline text="In the 1970s &lt;a href=&quot;https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Streaking&quot;&gt;streaking&lt;/a&gt; was a popular pastime.&amp;nbsp;" created="Thu, 01 Sep 2016 16:06:09 GMT" />
				<outline text="Out of nowhere people would be running around &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.google.com/search?q=streaker&amp;amp;safe=off&amp;amp;source=lnms&amp;amp;tbm=isch&amp;amp;sa=X&amp;amp;ved=0ahUKEwjBgd3Gyu7OAhVEF8AKHRtcDMUQ_AUICCgB&amp;amp;biw=1452&amp;amp;bih=1089&quot;&gt;naked&lt;/a&gt; in places where nakedness was frowned upon.&amp;nbsp;" created="Thu, 01 Sep 2016 16:06:10 GMT" />
				<outline text="For example, at a baseball game, a fan would run out on the field naked, and would have to be caught by police and taken off the field." created="Thu, 01 Sep 2016 16:06:11 GMT" />
				<outline text="They would do it so they could be on TV, and once they caught on to this, there was a rule that the camera would never go on the streaker.&amp;nbsp;" created="Thu, 01 Sep 2016 16:06:12 GMT" />
				<outline text="The streaking stopped." created="Thu, 01 Sep 2016 16:06:13 GMT" />
				<outline text="So maybe when a clearly Russian-contracted leak appears against the Democratic Party, and never against the Republicans, maybe the press could do what they did with streakers. Don't give them any attention.&amp;nbsp;" created="Thu, 01 Sep 2016 16:06:14 GMT" />
				</outline>
			</outline>
		<outline text="9/2/2016" created="Fri, 02 Sep 2016 13:50:12 GMT" >
			<outline text="Open letter to Marc Andreessen" created="Fri, 02 Sep 2016 13:50:12 GMT" type="outline" >
				<outline text="Marc, believe me, I'd never write an open letter like this if it weren't super important.&amp;nbsp;" created="Fri, 02 Sep 2016 13:50:13 GMT" />
				<outline text="As one of the founders of the web and a board member at Facebook, you're in a unique position to understand why it would be great to enable Facebook as a surface for bloggers to publish to." created="Fri, 02 Sep 2016 13:50:14 GMT" />
				<outline text="The goal: to get basic web features into the web version of Facebook.&amp;nbsp;

&lt;blockquote&gt;Links, simple styles (bold, italic), titles and podcasts.&lt;/blockquote&gt;

" created="Fri, 02 Sep 2016 13:50:15 GMT" />
				<outline text="With these features we could publish to Facebook and our blogs. Without this feature, bloggers have to cross-post manually, which is a problem, but because Facebook doesn't have linking, simple styles, titles and podcasts, a lot is missing from the Facebook versions. This vocabulary that has been evolving since the inception of the web in the early-mid 90s." created="Fri, 02 Sep 2016 13:50:16 GMT" />
				<outline text="&lt;span&gt;I've recorded a 15-minute podcast about this, linked into this blog post.&lt;/span&gt;" created="Fri, 02 Sep 2016 13:50:17 GMT" />
				<outline text="&lt;a href=&quot;http://scripting.com/2016/08/26/pleaseHelpFacebookSupportTheOpenWeb.html&quot;&gt;&lt;span data-auto-link=&quot;true&quot; data-href=&quot;http://scripting.com/2016/08/26/pleaseHelpFacebookSupportTheOpenWeb.html&quot;&gt;http://scripting.com/2016/08/26/pleaseHelpFacebookSupportTheOpenWeb.html&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/a&gt;" created="Fri, 02 Sep 2016 13:50:18 GMT" />
				<outline text="If you could listen and perhaps comment publicly, or advocate for it within Facebook, that would make a huge difference considering your central role in the creation of the web." created="Fri, 02 Sep 2016 13:50:19 GMT" />
				<outline text="Thanks! :-)" created="Fri, 02 Sep 2016 13:50:20 GMT" />
				</outline>
			<outline text="How the World Works, part I" created="Fri, 02 Sep 2016 18:16:17 GMT" type="outline" >
				<outline text="If you want a favor you're more likely to get it if you're &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.urbandictionary.com/define.php?term=connected&quot;&gt;connected&lt;/a&gt;.&amp;nbsp;&lt;span&gt;This is true in government, business, the press, education, charity, sports, etc.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;" created="Fri, 02 Sep 2016 18:16:18 GMT" />
				<outline text="For example, LeBron James is less likely to have a foul called on him than some random D-leaguer playing off the bench." created="Fri, 02 Sep 2016 18:16:19 GMT" />
				<outline text="If I have a friend in the government, I might call him or her up to get a good ticket to the inauguration. For that I might owe them a favor, which they may or may not call in." created="Fri, 02 Sep 2016 18:16:20 GMT" />
				<outline text="If you're a friend of one of the founders of Twitter you might have gotten a gift of as many as a million free followers in the early days before the press was watching. (And by the way some of the recipients were reporters. Is this even remotely ethical?)" created="Fri, 02 Sep 2016 18:16:21 GMT" />
				<outline text="If I leak to a reporter, I can ask for help promoting a new product. (Yes, journalists play this game too.)" created="Fri, 02 Sep 2016 18:16:22 GMT" />
				<outline text="&lt;i&gt;This is how the world works.&lt;/i&gt;&amp;nbsp;" created="Fri, 02 Sep 2016 18:16:23 GMT" />
				<outline text="The press reports news about the Clinton Foundation as if this is &lt;b&gt;not&lt;/b&gt; how the world works. Get them some &lt;a href=&quot;https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Smelling_salts&quot;&gt;smelling salts&lt;/a&gt;, bring in the &lt;a href=&quot;https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fainting_couch&quot;&gt;fainting couch&lt;/a&gt;, someone in government did a favor for the foundation that the boss started. (Except that didn't actually happen.)" created="Fri, 02 Sep 2016 18:16:24 GMT" />
				<outline text="I wonder if any of the press remembers how &lt;a href=&quot;https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dick_Cheney&quot;&gt;Dick Cheney&lt;/a&gt; went from Secretary of Defense to CEO of a large &lt;a href=&quot;https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Halliburton#Controversies&quot;&gt;defense contractor&lt;/a&gt;, then became VP, and they started a war that flowed huge amounts of government money to (wait for it) the very same defense contractor. Was this a scandal? Well, no actually they didn't think it was in Journalism World." created="Fri, 02 Sep 2016 18:16:25 GMT" />
				<outline text="&lt;span&gt;On a scale of 1 to 10 the outrage all this amounts to approx 0.00000001 compared to all the shit that's piled up about the &lt;i&gt;other candidate&lt;/i&gt; for President, which somehow does not create &quot;trust issues&quot; for him?&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;" created="Fri, 02 Sep 2016 18:16:26 GMT" />
				<outline text="PS: Why aren't the &lt;a href=&quot;https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Edward_Snowden&quot;&gt;Snowden&lt;/a&gt; revelations issues in this campaign? You want a scandal? Seems that's the real outrage. (I'm still voting for Clinton, btw.)" created="Fri, 02 Sep 2016 18:16:27 GMT" />
				</outline>
			<outline text="Hillary: We don't need the press" created="Fri, 02 Sep 2016 20:25:52 GMT" type="outline" >
				<outline text="A campaign is a time to talk about stuff that matters." created="Fri, 02 Sep 2016 20:25:53 GMT" />
				<outline text="That's why I was so &lt;a href=&quot;https://twitter.com/davewiner/status/771802500190068737&quot;&gt;happy&lt;/a&gt; to see that Hillary is &lt;a href=&quot;https://twitter.com/charlesornstein/status/771802351917301761&quot;&gt;bringing&lt;/a&gt; up the &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.statnews.com/2016/09/02/clinton-plan-drug-price/&quot;&gt;question&lt;/a&gt; of drug pricing. Huge. A real issue for so many people!&amp;nbsp;" created="Fri, 02 Sep 2016 20:25:54 GMT" />
				<outline text="Hillary if I could say one thing to you that you would hear it would be this.&amp;nbsp;&lt;span&gt;Up till now everything you've said to us, the voters, has been filtered through the press. And we both know they are terrible filters. They add so much of their own crap. They're looking for stuff that most of the time isn't there. And instead of saying it isn't there, they say it could have been there, and that's the &quot;scandal.&quot; But...&lt;/span&gt;" created="Fri, 02 Sep 2016 20:25:55 GMT" />
				<outline text="Here's the thing: WE DON'T NEED THE PRESS." created="Fri, 02 Sep 2016 20:25:56 GMT" />
				<outline text="You can talk straight to us. Use Twitter, use your blog, your podcast, Facebook, it's all good. Say what you want to say and forget about the press. They're going to be sour. We don't like them either. So let's not use them." created="Fri, 02 Sep 2016 20:25:57 GMT" />
				<outline text="Thanks for listening.&amp;nbsp;" created="Fri, 02 Sep 2016 20:25:58 GMT" />
				</outline>
			<outline text="Contact lens update" created="Fri, 02 Sep 2016 21:33:14 GMT" type="outline" >
				<outline text="Update on the contact lens situation." created="Fri, 02 Sep 2016 21:33:15 GMT" />
				<outline text="I pretty much can get the lens in and out. &amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;" created="Fri, 02 Sep 2016 21:33:16 GMT" />
				<outline text="I found the secret is to get really formal about the hand-washing part. Really clean the hands with hot water and soap. Use a nice towel to wipe everything perfectly dry, and special care with the fingers I'm going to use. It's healthy and it's also kind of a meditation, prepare the mind for the work to come." created="Fri, 02 Sep 2016 21:33:17 GMT" />
				<outline text="Then approach the mirror with confidence." created="Fri, 02 Sep 2016 21:33:18 GMT" />
				<outline text="I find that when the lens that has &quot;engaged&quot; with the eye it makes a few little popping sounds, as the air under the lens gets popped out. Once I hear that I know I can roll my finger off the lens and it will stay behind." created="Fri, 02 Sep 2016 21:33:19 GMT" />
				<outline text="When I have trouble it's because I didn't psych myself up for it." created="Fri, 02 Sep 2016 21:33:20 GMT" />
				</outline>
			</outline>
		<outline text="9/4/2016" created="Sun, 04 Sep 2016 15:51:57 GMT" >
			<outline text="Quick video weather in NYC?" created="Sun, 04 Sep 2016 15:51:57 GMT" type="outline" >
				<outline text="Where does everyone go for a quick video weather forecast for NYC?" created="Sun, 04 Sep 2016 15:51:58 GMT" />
				<outline text="You can send me a note on &lt;a href=&quot;https://twitter.com/davewiner/status/772466633025654784&quot;&gt;Twitter&lt;/a&gt;, or on &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.facebook.com/dave.winer.12/posts/476164525924291&quot;&gt;Facebook&lt;/a&gt;." created="Sun, 04 Sep 2016 15:51:59 GMT" />
				<outline text="I had this problem this morning, I still do. I used to go to weather.com, and never was very satisfied with how they approached it. This time there was a 1-minute commercial before the report. Sorry I don't stick around for that." created="Sun, 04 Sep 2016 15:52:00 GMT" />
				<outline text="I expect this is something they will eventually do very well on Facebook as they now do it for sports scores.&amp;nbsp;&lt;h4&gt;How it should work..&lt;/h4&gt;" created="Sun, 04 Sep 2016 15:52:01 GMT" />
				<outline text="TV integrated w the Internet or mobile should be:" created="Sun, 04 Sep 2016 15:52:02 GMT" />
				<outline text="&lt;ol&gt;&lt;li&gt;&lt;span&gt;Wish.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;&lt;span&gt;Gratification.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;&lt;span&gt;In a few seconds at most.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;&lt;/ol&gt;" created="Sun, 04 Sep 2016 15:52:03 GMT" />
				<outline text="" created="Sun, 04 Sep 2016 15:52:04 GMT" />
				<outline text="I had the same experience last year with &quot;find me a good podcast to listen to now.&quot; I have a &lt;a href=&quot;http://podcatch.com/&quot;&gt;great&lt;/a&gt; user experience for that but I expect I'm one of very few people.&lt;h4&gt;Dave gets on the pulpit..&lt;/h4&gt;" created="Sun, 04 Sep 2016 15:52:05 GMT" />
				<outline text="News industry, you keep leaving these big holes in what should be very simple problems to solve. Later you'll feel shut out when Facebook owns this. Act now." created="Sun, 04 Sep 2016 15:52:06 GMT" />
				</outline>
			<outline text="Ending an experiment" created="Sun, 04 Sep 2016 16:20:16 GMT" type="outline" >
				<outline text="Earlier this year I started cross-posting from &lt;a href=&quot;http://scripting.com/2016/09/04/endingAnExperiment.html&quot;&gt;this blog&lt;/a&gt; to Facebook and Medium. I'm no longer doing that." created="Sun, 04 Sep 2016 16:20:17 GMT" />
				<outline text="Here's why." created="Sun, 04 Sep 2016 16:20:18 GMT" />
				<outline text="First, if you put the two of them together, you'd have a great blogging surface. Medium handles linking, styles and titles. No podcasts, but that's the fourth item on the list for a reason. Most of my posts don't have podcasts attached. If there was one must-have feature I could live without that's the one (though giving up podcasting is giving up a huge win in interop). And Facebook handles updates, so if I make a change to a post after initially publishing it, those changes percolate to the Facebook version. So if you add the two together you get pretty close to the ideal." created="Sun, 04 Sep 2016 16:20:19 GMT" />
				<outline text="But Facebook doesn't do links, styling, titles or podcasts. And Medium doesn't do updates." created="Sun, 04 Sep 2016 16:20:20 GMT" />
				<outline text="I gave both a good shot, but the tradeoffs just aren't worth it." created="Sun, 04 Sep 2016 16:20:21 GMT" />
				<outline text="It's true more people read my full posts on Facebook than click the link to read it on my blog. By a pretty wide margin. But the limits are confusing my writing. My reason for writing is not just engagement, but also to get mind-to-mind connections. And my mind is confused when I write for this hybrid medium, and my blog suffers. I suffer. I'm more confused, and that's not a good thing.&amp;nbsp;" created="Sun, 04 Sep 2016 16:20:22 GMT" />
				<outline text="And Medium is published-and-done. I end up either manually updating the posts, or I put up with incomplete or inaccurate writing on Medium. It might be worth it to maintain two versions manually, if I was getting engagement on Medium, but there are very few comments or readers there. I think I've given it fair shot of most of a year. If it hasn't started happening yet, I figure it isn't going to happen.&amp;nbsp;" created="Sun, 04 Sep 2016 16:20:23 GMT" />
				<outline text="I'm back to posting links on Facebook, as I do on Twitter. And I'm thinking about posting links to Medium, so people who have been reading me there have a way of knowing when I've written a new post." created="Sun, 04 Sep 2016 16:20:24 GMT" />
				<outline text="If either of them change the way they work, I'll take another look.&amp;nbsp;" created="Sun, 04 Sep 2016 16:20:25 GMT" />
				</outline>
			</outline>
		<outline text="9/5/2016" created="Mon, 05 Sep 2016 14:28:57 GMT" >
			<outline text="What journalism is for" created="Mon, 05 Sep 2016 14:28:57 GMT" type="outline" >
				<outline text="&lt;span&gt;As I watch the coverage of the 2016 election continue, I am more desperate to change the way journalism covers politics.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;" created="Mon, 05 Sep 2016 14:28:58 GMT" />
				<outline text="An example. Yesterday on CNN, I finally heard a discussion of why they think HRC has a problem with honesty. They had tape of Clinton, which I listened to carefully. The reporters discussed it, I listened to that too.&amp;nbsp;" created="Mon, 05 Sep 2016 14:28:59 GMT" />
				<outline text="Net-net: I think she's telling the truth about how it worked, and the reporters were quite clear, that's not the story the American public wants to hear.&amp;nbsp;" created="Mon, 05 Sep 2016 14:29:00 GMT" />
				<outline text="Context: She was the top person in a 70,000 person &lt;a href=&quot;https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/United_States_Department_of_State&quot;&gt;organization&lt;/a&gt;, cc'd on lots of email, none of it secure, not just her server. It was not the only weak link.&amp;nbsp;" created="Mon, 05 Sep 2016 14:29:01 GMT" />
				<outline text="Think about how much email crosses your inbox and how much of you read carefully, and then imagine being at the top of such a large organization. It means most of what happens there is delegated.&amp;nbsp;" created="Mon, 05 Sep 2016 14:29:02 GMT" />
				<outline text="Did someone screw up? You have to look at the whole thing, and use your judgment and experience with how human organizations work. Even in the worst case, this doesn't merit much of our attention, imho. But only if you think of the voters as real people not an abstract concept.&amp;nbsp;" created="Mon, 05 Sep 2016 14:29:03 GMT" />
				<outline text="This frustration lead to a &lt;a href=&quot;https://twitter.com/davewiner/status/772234634327359488&quot;&gt;simple statement&lt;/a&gt; of what journalism is for.&lt;blockquote&gt;Journalism's most important job in covering an election is to help voters decide who would be the best choice.&lt;/blockquote&gt;" created="Mon, 05 Sep 2016 14:29:04 GMT" />
				<outline text="Maybe that doesn't fit with a theoretical idea of what journalism is for, but that's &lt;i&gt;what I want them to do, &lt;/i&gt;for me. I'm the person who watches their ads, who wants to be informed. I'm like a &lt;a href=&quot;http://scripting.com/davenet/1996/03/01/juryduty.html&quot;&gt;juror&lt;/a&gt;, and this is a trial. Who would make the better president. I, and all the other voters, have to decide." created="Mon, 05 Sep 2016 14:29:05 GMT" />
				<outline text="PS: Paul Krugman &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.nytimes.com/2016/09/05/opinion/hillary-clinton-gets-gored.html?_r=0&quot;&gt;explains&lt;/a&gt; my frustration better than I did.&amp;nbsp;" created="Mon, 05 Sep 2016 14:29:06 GMT" />
				</outline>
			<outline text="Narcos is good HBO-type violence" created="Mon, 05 Sep 2016 17:39:05 GMT" type="outline" >
				<outline text="I just finished bingeing &lt;a href=&quot;https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Narcos#Season_2&quot;&gt;season 2&lt;/a&gt; of Narcos." created="Mon, 05 Sep 2016 17:39:06 GMT" />
				<outline text="I really liked it. The whole thing, beginning to end.&amp;nbsp;" created="Mon, 05 Sep 2016 17:39:07 GMT" />
				<outline text="Now that I'm finished I find the background chatter in my brain is Spanish, with lots of curse words mixed in. It was like watching Deadwood, which made me talk like the barkeep &lt;a href=&quot;https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Al_Swearengen&quot;&gt;Swearengen&lt;/a&gt;. Cocksucker this guy, cocksucker that one. Or The Wire which taught my inner-voice to speak like a black man in Baltimore. Now I speak to myself in Spanish, not having much of an idea what I'm talking about, but I do know what &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.urbandictionary.com/define.php?term=puta&quot;&gt;puta&lt;/a&gt; means and &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.urbandictionary.com/define.php?term=puta%20madre&quot;&gt;puta madre&lt;/a&gt;. It seems in Spanish they use that word a lot especially &lt;a href=&quot;https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pablo_Escobar&quot;&gt;Pablo Escobar&lt;/a&gt;. I know how to pronounce Pablo btw, the b is almost but not quite silent. And I know how to tell someone to &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.spanishdict.com/answers/192032/if-i-ask-someone-to-calm-down-should-i-say-tranquila-or-tranquilo&quot;&gt;relax&lt;/a&gt; in Spanish.&amp;nbsp;" created="Mon, 05 Sep 2016 17:39:08 GMT" />
				<outline text="Maybe that's what made Narcos so interesting. It's mostly in Spanish with English subtitles. So I was able to learn and practice a new language while watching it. I like doing that." created="Mon, 05 Sep 2016 17:39:09 GMT" />
				<outline text="There's a great line near the end of the last episode which will be iconic among Narcos fans, because it's such a surprise and so well done. I'm not going to spoil it here, for that you'll have to &lt;a href=&quot;http://scripting.com/2016/09/05/spoiler.png&quot;&gt;click a link&lt;/a&gt;.&amp;nbsp;" created="Mon, 05 Sep 2016 17:39:10 GMT" />
				<outline text="Anyway if you like The Sopranos, or Deadwood, The Wire or any other violent HBO-type series, Narcos is for you.&amp;nbsp;" created="Mon, 05 Sep 2016 17:39:11 GMT" />
				</outline>
			</outline>
		<outline text="9/6/2016" created="Tue, 06 Sep 2016 14:59:14 GMT" >
			<outline text="Please RT: Poll re Trump's tax returns." created="Tue, 06 Sep 2016 14:59:14 GMT" type="outline" >
				<outline text="Donald Trump &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.politico.com/story/2016/09/trump-taxes-people-dont-care-227763&quot;&gt;said&lt;/a&gt; in an interview with ABC News that people don't care about his tax returns.&amp;nbsp;

" created="Tue, 06 Sep 2016 14:59:15 GMT" />
				<outline text="So I created a &lt;a href=&quot;https://twitter.com/davewiner/status/773171990245019649&quot;&gt;Twitter poll&lt;/a&gt; asking the question." created="Tue, 06 Sep 2016 14:59:16 GMT" />
				<outline text="&lt;a href=&quot;https://twitter.com/davewiner/status/773171990245019649&quot;&gt;&lt;span data-auto-link=&quot;true&quot; data-href=&quot;https://twitter.com/davewiner/status/773171990245019649&quot;&gt;https://twitter.com/davewiner/status/773171990245019649&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/a&gt;

" created="Tue, 06 Sep 2016 14:59:17 GMT" />
				<outline text="You can vote yourself, and even better RT it so everyone gets a chance to say what they think.

" created="Tue, 06 Sep 2016 14:59:18 GMT" />
				<outline text="Here's why it's important and it's just a start of the financial disclosures we need from Trump. We need to know who he does business with, and who he owes money to. He's the first billionaire to run for President. Or so he says. Let's see if he's telling the truth. There's so much at stake, and I think he's wrong, people very much do care about who he's in debt to and who he's in business with. What are his conflicts of interest?&amp;nbsp;

" created="Tue, 06 Sep 2016 14:59:19 GMT" />
				<outline text="Also this should not be a referendum on who does or does not support Trump. Even if you plan to vote for him, you need as much information as you can get about who you're voting for." created="Tue, 06 Sep 2016 14:59:20 GMT" />
				</outline>
			<outline text="Why RSS 2.0 lives at Harvard, not MIT" created="Tue, 06 Sep 2016 15:41:06 GMT" type="outline" >
				<outline text="I was just reminded why I went with Harvard as the place where the &lt;a href=&quot;https://cyber.harvard.edu/rss/rss.html&quot;&gt;RSS 2.0 spec&lt;/a&gt; resides permanently. And why the further work on &lt;a href=&quot;http://scripting.com/2015/09/30/aPodcastAboutPodcasting.html&quot;&gt;podcasting&lt;/a&gt;, resulting a great new medium in the last few years, happened there as well.&amp;nbsp;Harvard deserves a lot of credit for enabling that. " created="Tue, 06 Sep 2016 15:41:07 GMT" />
				<outline text="So why did I push so hard to do the work at Harvard, instead of MIT which would seem a more straightforward choice? The two universities, at opposite ends of &lt;a href=&quot;https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Massachusetts_Avenue_(metropolitan_Boston)&quot;&gt;Mass Ave&lt;/a&gt; in Cambridge have great reps, but at opposite ends of the spectrum between engineering and the humanities." created="Tue, 06 Sep 2016 15:41:08 GMT" />
				<outline text="I've always believed that it was the human side of technology that had the greatest potential. When I was coming up in the 70s and 80s this was a contrarian view. So in 2003 when RSS needed a home to cement it as a standard, I chose the Cambridge university with the stronger rep as a place to be human as opposed to being a nerd. Not that the two are in any way exclusive. My point was, that through the technology we were working on, they would become the same thing." created="Tue, 06 Sep 2016 15:41:09 GMT" />
				<outline text="I guess the disadvantage of going the contrarian route is that it isn't so intuitive to the people at &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.harvard.edu/&quot;&gt;Harvard&lt;/a&gt; today that the university should have played such a great role at the leading edge of technology thirteen years ago.&amp;nbsp;" created="Tue, 06 Sep 2016 15:41:10 GMT" />
				<outline text="&lt;span&gt;No small thanks to the people at &lt;/span&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;https://cyber.harvard.edu/&quot;&gt;Berkman Center&lt;/a&gt;&lt;span&gt; for their love and support at the time. ;-)&lt;/span&gt;" created="Tue, 06 Sep 2016 15:41:11 GMT" />
				<outline text="And in retrospect -- it worked. Took a long time to shake out. But all is quiet in RSS-land and it still rages as a standard for interop that continues to bear fruit." created="Tue, 06 Sep 2016 15:41:12 GMT" />
				</outline>
